### Medieval Officeholder

This article delves into the multifaceted role of the medieval officeholder, known by various designations that ultimately converge on a similar administrative and protective function. It is crucial to distinguish this historical position from its modern legal counterparts. For the contemporary legal professional, one might consult the entry on [Advocate](/Advocate). Similarly, the modern French legal office is addressed under [Avoué](/Avou%C3%A9). For those interested in the surname, [Vogt (surname)](/Vogt_(surname)) and [Voogd (surname)](/Voogd_(surname)) provide relevant context, while [Vogt, Germany](/Vogt,_Germany) pertains to a geographical location.

This particular article, however, requires more rigorous substantiation. It is in need of additional citations to ensure its [verification](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). Readers and contributors are encouraged to assist in [improving this article](/Special:EditPage/Advocatus) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners). Without them, certain material may be subject to challenge and subsequent removal. To aid in this endeavor, one can [find sources](/Special:Search?search=%22Advocatus%22&go=Go) through news archives, scholarly journals, and reputable books, including resources like JSTOR. (January 2019) ( [Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal) )

This piece is part of a broader series on [Imperial, royal, noble, and chivalric ranks in Europe](/Imperial,_royal_and_noble_ranks), exploring the intricate hierarchy and titles that shaped the medieval world.

